column1: /**\n * An "async function" in the context of Async is an asynchronous function with\n * a variable number of parameters
column2: with the final parameter being a callback.\n * (`function (arg1
column5: callback) {}`)\n * The final callback is of the form `callback(err
column7:
which must be
 * called once the function is completed.  The callback should be called with a
 * Error as its first argument to signal that an error occurred.
 * Otherwise
column9: it should be called with `null` as the first\n * argument
column10: and any additional `result` arguments that may apply
column11: to signal\n * successful completion.\n * The callback must be called exactly once
column12:
ideally on a later tick of the
 * JavaScript event loop.
 *
 * This type of function is also referred to as a "Node-style async function"
column13: \n * or a "continuation passing-style function" (CPS). Most of the methods of this\n * library are themselves CPS/Node-style async functions
column14:
or functions that
 * return CPS/Node-style async functions.
 *
 * Wherever we accept a Node-style async function
column15: we also directly accept an\n * [ES2017 `async` function]{@link https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/async_function}.\n * In this case
column16: the `async` function will not be passed a final callback\n * argument
column17: and any thrown error will be used as the `err` argument of the\n * implicit callback
column18: and the return value will be used as the `result` value.\n * (i.e. a `rejected` of the returned Promise becomes the `err` callback\n * argument
column19: and a `resolved` value becomes the `result`.)\n *\n * Note
column21:
we can only detect native `async`
 * functions and not transpilied implementations.
 * Your environment must have `async`/`await` support for this to work.
 * (e.g. Node > v7.6
column22: or a recent version of a modern browser).\n * If you are using `async` functions through a transpiler (e.g. Babel)
column23: you\n * must still wrap the function with [asyncify]{@link module:Utils.asyncify}
column24:
* because the `async function` will be compiled to an ordinary function that
 * returns a promise.
 *
 * @typedef {Function} AsyncFunction
 * @static
 */Comment.Multiline

column1: /**\n * Async is a utility module which provides straight-forward
column2:
powerful functions
 * for working with asynchronous JavaScript. Although originally designed for
 * use with [Node.js](http://nodejs.org) and installable via
 * `npm install --save async`
column3:
it can also be used directly in the browser.
 * @module async
 * @see AsyncFunction
 */Comment.Multiline

column1: /**\n * A collection of `async` functions for manipulating collections
column2:
such as
 * arrays and objects.
 * @module Collections
 */Comment.Multiline
